DURING FISCAL 2012, THE MACROECONOMIC ENVIRONMENT IN JAPAN REMAINED UNCERTAIN AS THE MARKET CONTINUED TO RECOVER FROM THE EFFECTS OF THE EARTHQUAKE AND TSUNAMI THAT OCCURRED IN MARCH 2011. ON A CURRENCY NEUTRAL BASIS, FOOTWEAR REVENUE IN JAPAN INCREASED 3% FOR FISCAL 2012, AS GROWTH IN RUNNING AND FOOTBALL (SOCCER) MORE THAN OFFSET A DECLINE IN SPORTSWEAR.

EXCLUDING CHANGES IN CURRENCY EXCHANGE RATES, APPAREL REVENUE DECREASED 1% FOR FISCAL 2012, AS THE DECLINE IN SPORTSWEAR MORE THAN OFFSET THE GROWTH IN RUNNING AND FOOTBALL (SOCCER).

ON A REPORTED BASIS, EBIT FOR JAPAN GREW AT A FASTER RATE THAN REVENUE AS A RESULT OF IMPROVED GROSS MARGIN AND LEVERAGE OF SELLING AND ADMINISTRATIVE EXPENSES. THE INCREASE IN JAPAN’S GROSS MARGIN WAS MAINLY DRIVEN BY THE FAVORABLE IMPACT FROM THE YEAR-OVER-YEAR CHANGE IN STANDARD CURRENCY RATES, A DECREASE IN INVENTORY OBSOLESCENCE EXPENSE AS WELL AS A LOWER MIX OF CLOSE-OUT SALES. THESE FAVORABLE IMPACTS WERE PARTIALLY OFFSET BY HIGHER PRODUCT INPUT COSTS.

